title: Grateful Dead Live at Miami Arena on 1994-04-06
lineage: Schoeps MK4 (FOB) > Panasonic SV-250 > DAT > CDR > EAC0.9 beta 4 (secure) > CD Wave > shntool > SHN
description: Jack Straw, Jack A Roe, Wang Dang Doodle, Broken Arrow, West L.A. Fadeaway, El Paso*, Row Jimmy, Promised Land Here Comes Sunshine, Samson & Delilah, Cumberland Blues, Way to Go Home, Women Are Smarter, Drums-> Space-> The Wheel, All Along The Watchtower, Standing On the Moon, E: Johnny B. Goode

reviews.review_text: Strong show for 94 This show makes up for the lackluster Orlando show the night before. This was one of my favorite shows that I ever attended live. We met Toby "Gainesville" Gaine on the Train (Metrorail) on the way in, a great friend to this day. Then we get a pair of Jacks to open, a strong Promised to close the first set, our first Cumberland since the Vegas lightning show in 92 (I tackled Tim to the floor when they went into it), and the best Standing on the Moon I ever heard. I've put it on countless compilations. Jerry just goes OFF vocally at the end. Makes me cry every time.

Best song Ever I wasn't a big fan of changin soundmen from Healy but...... this Standing on the moon is the single best song I have ever heard in concert.  Jerry voice and guitar go popsicle and melt all over your ears!
tito tito shut the fuck up, how the hell would u know whats scripted, this is one of the best ive heard, the one from 91 u talk about tito is very good but its not the best either shitbrick

Thats some funny shit.. As far as Standing on the moon goes I like the 89 versions best as far as the "be with you part"
I think Jerry enjoyed doing it and the crowd got off on it when Jerry belted those out just like the end of So Many Roads with "ease my soul" I don't think it was a scripted thing as time went on esp. towards late with exception of hot shows or moments Jerry was tired and wearing thin and 
unfortunately you could see and hear this 
happening. Still to this day and right now as matter of fact I like to find hot little nugs of Jerry with his 30 year on the road experience in  these later Dead shows of 92,93,94 or 95
some moments of genius guitar solos from heaven or like how He accentuates certain verses on any night like the "nothin comes for free" part on Stella Blue 3-21-94 in Ohio. The Cumberland Blues here was pretty good nice picking crowd was into it. 
  Lookin' for more later..

SOTM This SOTM rivals the AM Dew on 3-27-94, and the Stella on 3-21-94, although I think the AM Dew and the Stella are probably better, this is soulful and emotional Garcia at his absolute finest....If you think that 94 sucked (and I know a lot of the Heads out there do), at least do me the service of listening to any of the aforementioned versions and then re-evaluate your opinion. 

REVISION: Hey bigboypeete, thanks for putting Tito in his place, some of the things he says about people who simply disagree with him are flat our RUDE!!
sotm 9-10-91 w/branford on sax would also be one I would check out.
what a cool show this was the first dead show i attended. blew my mind! great to be able to listen to it again

My favorite show of 94... ...and I saw 7.  This night was especially fun as a friend and I took 2 girls for their first show.  We went up to the top of the arena, directly opposite the stage.  The whole 2nd set rocked, and I especially liked the 2nd set Cumberland and the light show accompanying the Wheel.  Incidentally, the 2 RFK shows were the worst of those that I ever saw (92, 93, 94, and 95)--just low energy. The coolest seen was Buckeye--coldest August night I ever spent.

SOTM People have been writing that this is the best "Standing"ever.Im a big SOTM fan,and 6-7-91 was by far the best ever,killing this crappy audience version.Sure Jerry goes off at the end,but by this time it was a bit rehearsed,he blew many a "Standing"in the last couple years and would try to make it up with a seemingly scripted"BE WITH YOU!"session at the end.It wasnt even cool man.Again,check out 6-7-91.Its fucking sick as fuck
Best Standing on the Moon ever Listen to Jerry go off at the end of SOTM. The high point of my 47 shows with good ole Uncle Jer.
